gether specially commissioned contributions by leading housing experts who explore a wide range of themes and issues affecting the prospects for the coming 20 years or more. Drawing on the evidence of the past and present they analyse the implications of current trends to consider how markets and governments might respond to the challenges ahead. The book is not a work of prophecy or a manifesto for action. It is designed to stimulate and contribute to informed debate about possible futures and what can be done to influence what happens. Building on the past will be of interest to all those concerned about the future of housing, neighbourhoods and communities over the next 20 years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHousingzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Rowland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBest, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBramley, Glen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairncross, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairncross, Liz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCooper, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeather, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalpass, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalpass, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorgan, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurie, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNevin, Brendan, econt